The reason to have Allen back is that the Biden administration just announc=
ed a major new wave of export controls ( https://www.bis.gov/press-release/=
commerce-strengthens-export-controls-restrict-chinas-capability-produce-adv=
anced ) ; these new controls come as the previous wave of chip controls has=
 come under significant criticism, including from Sharp China ( https://sha=
rpchina.fm/member/episode/myriad-holes-in-us-chip-controls-new-reports-on-t=
smc-and-huawei-the-latest-stimulus-news-mixed-signals-on-private-tutoring )=
 and Allen ( https://www.csis.org/analysis/true-impact-allied-export-contro=
ls-us-and-chinese-semiconductor-manufacturing-equipment ).

To that end, Allen has a new report out about the latest chip controls ( ht=
tps://www.csis.org/analysis/understanding-biden-administrations-updated-exp=
ort-controls ) , which guides our discussion. We cover the expansion to hig=
h-bandwidth memory, the distinction between country and entity bans, and wh=
y the Biden administration may have been suffering from magical thinking in=
 terms of trying to stop AI while still preserving U.S. semiconductor equip=
ment sales. We also discuss the dramatic expansion of the of the Foreign Di=
rect Product Rule, the implications for Nvidia, and what may or may not cha=
nge under a Trump administration. In addition, we touch briefly on Allen=E2=
=80=99s recent report on the Biden administration=E2=80=99s latest national=
 security memorandum on AI ( https://www.csis.org/analysis/biden-administra=
tions-national-security-memorandum-ai-explained ) , and how the U.S. can sa=
